can swap the element at i = 3 to obtain nums1 = [1,2,3,4] and nums2 = [5,6,7,8].\n\nReturn the minimum number of needed operations to make nums1 and nums2 strictly increasing. The test cases are generated so that the given input always makes it possible.\nAn array arr is strictly increasing if and only if arr[0] < arr[1] < arr[2] < ... < arr[arr.length - 1].\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: nums1 = [1,3,5,4], nums2 = [1,2,3,7]\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: \nSwap nums1[3] and nums2[3]. Then the sequences are:\nnums1 = [1, 3, 5, 7] and nums2 = [1, 2, 3, 4]\nwhich are both strictly increasing.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: nums1 = [0,3,5,8,9], nums2 = [2,1,4,6,9]\nOutput: 1\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n2 <= nums1.length <= 105\nnums2.length == nums1.length\n0 <= nums1[i], nums2[i] <= 2 * 105\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minSwap(self, nums1: List[int], nums2: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "To solve this problem, we can use dynamic programming to keep track of the minimum number of swaps needed to make both arrays strictly increasing up to each index. We'll maintain two arrays for dynamic programming:\n\n- `keep[i]`: The minimum number of swaps needed to make both arrays strictly increasing up to index `i` without swapping `nums1[i]` and `nums2[i]`.\n- `swap[i]`: The minimum number of swaps needed to make both arrays strictly increasing up to index `i` with swapping `nums1[i]` and `nums2[i]`.\n\nHere's the step-by-step solution using dynamic programming:\n\n1. Initialize `keep[0]` to 0 because no swap is needed for the first element.\n2. Initialize `swap[0]` to 1 because one swap is needed for the first element to make it part of the solution.\n3. For each subsequent index `i`:\n   - If both `nums1[i-1] < nums1[i]` and `nums2[i-1] < nums2[i]` and `nums1[i-1] < nums2[i]` and `nums2[i-1] < nums1[i]`, it means both configurations (swapping or not swapping) can be used independently, and we choose the minimum of the two previous options with the appropriate adjustment.\n   - Otherwise, we need to ensure the sequence remains strictly increasing, and we take the previous option that allows this with the necessary swap.\n\nHere is the Python code implementing this logic:\n\n```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def minSwap(self, nums1: List[int], nums2: List[int]) -> int:\n        n = len(nums1)\n        keep = [0] * n\n        swap = [0] * n\n        \n        # Base case\n        keep[0] = 0\n        swap[0] = 1\n        \n        for i in range(1, n):\n            if nums1[i-1] < nums1[i] and nums2[i-1] < nums2[i]:\n                if nums1[i-1] < nums2[i] and nums2[i-1] < nums1[i]:\n                    keep[i] = min(keep[i-1], swap[i-1])\n                    swap[i] = min(keep[i-1], swap[i-1]) + 1\n                else:\n                    keep[i] = keep[i-1]\n                    swap[i] = swap[i-1] + 1\n            else:\n                keep[i] = swap[i-1]\n                swap[i] = keep[i-1] + 1\n        \n        return min(keep[n-1], swap[n-1])\n```\n\nExplanation of the code:\n- We initialize `keep[0]` to 0 and `swap[0]` to 1.\n- For each index `i` from 1 to `n-1`, we check the conditions:\n  - If both sequences can be maintained in strictly increasing order without considering the swap or swap conditions independently, we take the minimum of the previous states.\n  - Otherwise, we ensure the sequence remains strictly increasing by taking the necessary swap or no swap from the previous state.\n- Finally, we return the minimum of the last elements of `keep` and `swap` arrays, which gives us the minimum number of swaps needed to make both arrays strictly increasing.\n\nThis solution runs in O(n) time complexity with O(n) space complexity, which can be further optimized to O(1) space by only keeping track of the last 